  <paragraphs>
    <title>Inverse Trigonometric Functions and Right Triangles</title>
    <p></p>
    <p>
      In the section titled "The Inverse Trigonometric Functions,"  trigonometric identities are used to determine the value of expressions such as <m>\cos\left(\tan^{-1}\left(\frac{4}{3}\right)\right)</m>.  In this section we will explore an alternative strategy that makes use of right triangle trigonometry.  Let's see a couple of examples.
    </p>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Use a right triangle to determine the value of <m>\cos\left(\tan^{-1}\left(\frac{4}{3}\right)\right)</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Let's define <m>\theta</m> using the equation <m>\theta=\tan^{-1}\left(\frac{4}{3}\right)</m>.  We immediately know two things about <m>\theta</m>.
          <me>\tan(\theta)=\frac{4}{3}</me>
          <me>0^\circ \le \theta \le 180^{\circ}</me>
          Since <m>\tan(\theta) \gt 0</m>, we can further restrict the range of  <m>\theta</m> as follows.
          <me>0^{\circ} \lt \theta \lt 90^{\circ}</me>
          Because the value of <m>\theta</m> must fall strictly between <m>0^{\circ}</m> and <m>90^{\circ}</m>, we can think of it as the angle of a right triangle.  We can diagram said triangle in such a way that the ratio of the side opposite to <m>\theta</m> and the side adjacent to <m>\theta</m> is <m>\frac{4}{3}</m>, that is
          <me>\frac{\text{OPP}}{\text{ADJ}}=\frac{4}{3}.</me>
          The most straight forward way to create that ratio is to simply assign the value of <m>4</m> to <m>\text{OPP}</m> and the value of <m>3</m> to <m>\text{ADJ}</m>.  This is done in <xref ref="trigonometry-right-triangles-figure-9">Figure</xref>.  The value assigned to the hypotenuse was calculated using the Pythagorean theorem.  That calculation is shown below.  
          <md>
            <mrow>\text{HYP}^2\amp=3^2+4^2</mrow>
            <mrow>\text{HYP}^2\amp=9+16</mrow>
            <mrow>\text{HYP}^2\amp=25</mrow>
            <mrow>\text{HYP}\amp=5</mrow>
          </md>
          We now have all of the necessary information to determine the value of <m>\cos\left(\tan^{-1}\left(\frac{4}{3}\right)\right)</m> and we do so below.
        </p>
        <sidebyside widths="57% 37%" margins="0%">

          <p>
            <md>
              <mrow>\cos\left(\tan^{-1}\left(\frac{4}{3}\right)\right)\amp=\cos(\theta)</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp=\frac{\text{ADJ}}{\text{HYP}}</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp=\frac{3}{5}</mrow>
            </md>
          </p>

          <figure xml:id="trigonometry-right-triangles-figure-9">
            <caption>SOH CAH TOA</caption>
            <image>
              <description>
                  A right triangle with one of the acute angles labeled <m>\theta</m>.  The side opposite of <m>\theta</m> is labeled <m>4</m>.  The side adjacent to <m>\theta</m> is labeled <m>3</m>.  The hypotenuse is labeled <m>5</m>.
              </description>
              <latex-image-code>
                <![CDATA[
                  \begin{tikzpicture}
                    \draw (0,0) -- (6,0) node[midway, below] {$3$} -- (6,8) node[midway, right] {$4$} -- (0,0) node[midway, above left] {$5$};
                    \draw (0.5,0) arc (0:55.13:.5);
                    \draw (0.95,0.5) node{$\theta$};
                    \draw (5.5,0) -- (5.5,0.5) -- (6,0.5);
                  \end{tikzpicture}
                ]]>
              </latex-image-code>
            </image>
          </figure>

        </sidebyside>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Use a right triangle to determine the value of <m>\tan\left(\sin^{-1}\left(\frac{3}{7}\right)\right)</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Let's define <m>\theta</m> using the equation <m>\theta=\sin^{-1}\left(\frac{3}{7}\right)</m>.  We immediately know two things about <m>\theta</m>.
          <me>\sin(\theta)=\frac{3}{7}</me>
          <me>0^\circ \le \theta \le 180^{\circ}</me>
          Since <m>\sin(\theta) \gt 0</m>, we can further restrict the range of  <m>\theta</m> as follows.
          <me>0^{\circ} \lt \theta \lt 90^{\circ}</me>
          Because the value of <m>\theta</m> must fall strictly between <m>0^{\circ}</m> and <m>90^{\circ}</m>, we can think of it as the angle of a right triangle.  We can diagram said triangle in such a way that the ratio of the side opposite to <m>\theta</m> and the hypotenuse is <m>\frac{3}{7}</m>, that is
          <me>\frac{\text{OPP}}{\text{HYP}}=\frac{3}{7}.</me>
          The most straight forward way to create that ratio is to simply assign the value of <m>3</m> to <m>\text{OPP}</m> and the value of <m>7</m> to <m>\text{HYP}</m>.  This is done in <xref ref="trigonometry-right-triangles-figure-10">Figure</xref>.  The value assigned to the adjacent side was calculated using the Pythagorean theorem.  That calculation is shown below.  
          <md>
            <mrow>\text{ADJ}^2+3^2\amp=7^2</mrow>
            <mrow>\text{ADJ}^2+9\amp=49</mrow>
            <mrow>\text{ADJ}^2\amp=40</mrow>
            <mrow>\text{ADJ}\amp=\sqrt{40}</mrow>
            <mrow>\text{ADJ}\amp=2\sqrt{10}</mrow>
          </md>
          We now have all of the necessary information to determine the value of <m>\tan\left(\sin^{-1}\left(\frac{3}{7}\right)\right)</m> and we do so below.
        </p>
        <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">

          <p>
            <md>
              <mrow>\tan\left(\sin^{-1}\left(\frac{3}{7}\right)\right)\amp=\tan(\theta)</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp=\frac{\text{OPP}}{\text{ADJ}}</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp=\frac{3}{2\sqrt{10}}</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp=\frac{3}{2\sqrt{10}} \cdot \frac{\sqrt{10}}{\sqrt{10}}</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp=\frac{3\sqrt{10}}{20}</mrow>
            </md>
          </p>

          <figure xml:id="trigonometry-right-triangles-figure-10">
            <caption>SOH CAH TOA</caption>
            <image>
              <description>
                  A right triangle with one of the acute angles labeled <m>\theta</m>.  The side opposite of <m>\theta</m> is labeled <m>3</m>.  The side adjacent to <m>\theta</m> is labeled <m>2\sqrt{10}</m>.  The hypotenuse is labeled <m>7</m>.
              </description>
              <latex-image-code>
                <![CDATA[
                  \begin{tikzpicture}
                    \draw (0,0) -- (6.32,0) node[midway, below] {$2\sqrt{10}$} -- (6.32,3) node[midway, right] {$3$} -- (0,0) node[midway, above left] {$7$};
                    \draw (0.5,0) arc (0:25.78:.5);
                    \draw (0.95,0.25) node{$\theta$};
                    \draw (5.82,0) -- (5.82,0.5) -- (6.32,0.5);
                  \end{tikzpicture}
                ]]>
              </latex-image-code>
            </image>
          </figure>

        </sidebyside>
      </solution>
    </example>

  </paragraphs>

  <exercises>
    <exercisegroup>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Determine the missing pieces of each right triangle.
        </p>
      </introduction>

      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">

            <p>
              Determine the missing parts of the triangle shown in <xref ref="trigonometry-right-triangles-exercises-figure-1">Figure</xref>.  Round the angular measurements to the nearest tenth of a degree.
            </p>

            <figure xml:id="trigonometry-right-triangles-exercises-figure-1">
              <caption>Determine the Missing Parts of the Triangle</caption>
              <image>
                <description>
                  A right triangle with one of the acute angles labeled alpha and the other acute angle labeled beta.  The side opposite alpha is labeled <m>a</m> and the side opposite beta is labeled <m>15</m>.  The hypotenuse is labeled <m>17</m>.
                </description>
                <latex-image-code>
                  <![CDATA[
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                      \draw (0,4.27) -- (8,4.27) node[midway, above]{$15$} -- (8,0) node[midway, right] {$a$} -- (0,4.27) node[midway, below left] {$17$};
                      \draw (0.48,4) arc (328:360:.5);
                      \draw (0.85,4.08) node{$\alpha$};
                      \draw (8,0.45) arc (90:148:.5);
                      \draw (7.65,0.8) node{$\beta$};
                      \draw (7.5,4.27) -- (7.5,3.77) -- (8,3.77);
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                  ]]>
                </latex-image-code>
              </image>
            </figure>
          </sidebyside>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            Let's begin by using the Pythagorean theorem to determine the value of <m>a</m>.
            <md>
              <mrow>a^2+15^2\amp=17^2</mrow>
              <mrow>a^2+225\amp=289</mrow>
              <mrow>a^2\amp=64</mrow>
              <mrow>a\amp=8</mrow>
            </md>
            From the perspective of <m>\alpha</m>, the opposite side is <m>a</m>, which we now know is equal to <m>8</m>.  This gives the following.
            <me>\sin(\alpha)=\frac{8}{17}\,\,\Longrightarrow\,\,\alpha=\sin^{-1}\left(\frac{8}{15}\right)</me>
            Using my trusty calculator, I learn that
            <me>\alpha \approx 28.1^{\circ}.</me>
            From the perspective of <m>\beta</m>, the opposite side is <m>15</m>.  Thus we have the following.
            <me>\sin(\beta)=\frac{15}{17}\,\,\Longrightarrow\,\,\beta=\sin^{-1}\left(\frac{15}{17}\right)</me>
            Again relying upon my calculator, I get the following result.
            <me>\beta \approx 61.9^{\circ}</me>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">

            <p>
              Determine the missing parts of the triangle shown in <xref ref="trigonometry-right-triangles-exercises-figure-2">Figure</xref>.  Round the side measurements to the nearest integer.
            </p>

            <figure xml:id="trigonometry-right-triangles-exercises-figure-2">
              <caption>Determine the Missing Parts of the Triangle</caption>
              <image>
                <description>
                  A right triangle with one of the acute angles labeled alpha and the other acute angle labeled <m>73.74^{\circ}</m>.  The side opposite alpha is labeled <m>7</m> and the side opposite the <m>73.74^{\circ}</m> angle is labeled <m>b</m>.  The hypotenuse is labeled <m>r</m>.
                </description>
                <latex-image-code>
                  <![CDATA[
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                      \draw (0,0) -- (8,0) node[midway, below]{$b$} -- (8,2.3) node[midway, right] {$7$} -- (0,0) node[midway, above] {$r$};
                      \draw (7.55,2.18) arc (200:270:0.5);
                      \draw (7.2,1.5) node{$73.74^{\circ$};
                      \draw (0.5,0) arc (0:16.6:0.5);
                      \draw (1.3,0.2) node{$\alpha$};
                      \draw (8,0.5) -- (7.5,0.5) -- (7.5,0);
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                  ]]>
                </latex-image-code>
              </image>
            </figure>
          </sidebyside>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            Because the angles of a triangle add to <m>180^{\circ}</m>, we can easily determine <m>\alpha</m>, which is done below.
            <md>
              <mrow>\alpha\amp=180^{\circ}-90^{\circ}-73.74^{\circ}</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp=16.26^{\circ}</mrow>
            </md> 
            Relative to <m>\alpha</m>, the side labeled <m>7</m> is the opposite side.  We can use <m>\sin(\alpha)</m> to determine <m>r</m>.  Relative to the <m>73.74^{\circ}</m>, the side labeled <m>b</m> is the opposite side.  We can use <m>\tan\left(73.74^{\circ}\right)</m> to determine <m>b</m>.  These tasks are performed below.
          </p>
          <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">

            <p>
              <md>
                <mrow>\sin(\alpha)\amp=\frac{7}{r}</mrow>
                <mrow>r\sin(\alpha)\amp=7</mrow>
                <mrow>r\amp=\frac{7}{\sin\left(16.6^{\circ}\right)}</mrow>
                <mrow>r \amp\approx 25</mrow>
              </md>
            </p>

            <p>
              <md>
                <mrow>\tan\left(73.74^{\circ}\right)\amp=\frac{b}{7}</mrow>
                <mrow>7\tan\left(73.74^{\circ}\right)\amp=b</mrow>
                <mrow>24 \amp\approx b</mrow>
              </md>
            </p>

          </sidebyside>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">

            <p>
              Determine the missing parts of the triangle shown in <xref ref="trigonometry-right-triangles-exercises-figure-3">Figure</xref>. Make sure that all radical expressions are fully simplified.
            </p>

            <figure xml:id="trigonometry-right-triangles-exercises-figure-3">
              <caption>Determine the Missing Parts of the Triangle</caption>
              <image>
                <description>
                  A right triangle with one of the acute angles labeled beta and the other acute angle labeled <m>60^{\circ}</m>.  The side opposite beta is labeled <m>12</m> and the side opposite the <m>60^{\circ}</m> angle is labeled <m>b</m>.  The hypotenuse is labeled <m>r</m>.
                </description>
                <latex-image-code>
                  <![CDATA[
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                      \draw (0,0) -- (0,4) node[midway, left]{$12$} -- (8,4) node[midway, above] {$b$} -- (0,0) node[midway, below] {$r$};
                      \draw (7.45,4) arc (180:210:.5);
                      \draw (6.8,3.71) node{$\beta$};
                      \draw (0.42,0.23) arc (30:90:.5);
                      \draw (0.6,1) node{$60^{\circ}$};
                      \draw (0,3.5) -- (0.5,3.5) -- (0.5,4);
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                  ]]>
                </latex-image-code>
              </image>
            </figure>
          </sidebyside>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            Clearly we're looking at a <m>30^{\circ}-60^{\circ}-90^{\circ}</m> triangle, so <m>\beta=30^{\circ}</m>.
          </p>  
          <p>
            Relative to the <m>60^{\circ}</m> angle, the side labeled <m>b</m> is the opposite side.  We can use <m>\tan\left(60^{\circ}\right)</m> to determine <m>b</m> and then use the Pythagorean theorem to determine the value of <m>r</m>.  This is all executed below.
            <md>
              <mrow>\tan\left(60^{\circ}\right)\amp=\frac{b}{12}</mrow>
              <mrow>12\tan\left(60^{\circ}\right)\amp=b</mrow>
              <mrow>12\sqrt{3}\amp=b</mrow>
            </md>
          </p>
          <p>
            <md>
              <mrow>r^2\amp=12^2+\left(12\sqrt{3}\right)^2</mrow>
              <mrow>r^2\amp=576</mrow>
              <mrow>r\amp=24</mrow>
            </md>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">

            <p>
              Determine the missing parts of the triangle shown in <xref ref="trigonometry-right-triangles-exercises-figure-4">Figure</xref>.  Round the angular measurements to the nearest tenth of a degree.  Make that all radical expressions are completely simplified.
            </p>

            <figure xml:id="trigonometry-right-triangles-exercises-figure-4">
