        <solution>
          <p>
            Let's begin by using the Pythagorean theorem to determine the value of <m>r</m>.
            <md>
              <mrow>r^2\amp=8^2+10^2</mrow>
              <mrow>r^2\amp=168</mrow>
              <mrow>r\amp=\sqrt{168}</mrow>
              <mrow>r\amp=2\sqrt{41}</mrow>
            </md>
          </p>
          <p>
            From the perspective of <m>\beta</m>, the side marked <m>8</m> is the opposite side.  We can use the sine function to determine <m>\beta</m> and then subtract the two known angles from <m>180^{\circ}</m> to determine the value of <m>\alpha</m>.  These actions take place below.
            <md>
              <mrow>\sin(\beta)\amp=\frac{8}{2\sqrt{41}}</mrow>
              <mrow>\beta\amp=\sin^{-1}\left(\frac{4}{\sqrt{41}}\right)</mrow>
              <mrow>\beta \amp\approx 38.7^{\circ}</mrow>
            </md>
          </p>
          <p>
            <md>
              <mrow>\alpha \amp\approx 180^{\circ}-90^{\circ}-38.7^{\circ}</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp=51.3^{\circ}</mrow>
            </md>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

